Problem 7.4 Each of these statements have an error. It might be an error in syntax or an error in the way the data tables are used, etc. Tell what are the error(s) in these expressions.

  1. BabyNames %>% group_by( "First" ) %>% summarise( votesReceived=n() )
    • Error: trying to get votesReceived from the wrong table. Number of cases in BabyNames does not reflect meaningful data on any kind of voting.
  2. Tmp <- group_by(BabyNames, year, sex ) %>% summarise( Tmp, totalBirths=sum(count))
    • Error: Trying to bind data table Tmp to summarise, but it has not been declared yet. It should be removed because BabyNames will be piped in. Also, because BabyNames is piped in, this function will try to use Tmp as a variable binding, which will cause an error.
  3. Tmp <- group_by(BabyNames, year, sex) summarise( BabyNames, totalBirths=sum(count) )
    • Error: Missing a piping symbol. This will cause an unexpected symbol error because R does not understand the connection between group_by and summarise. Note: Can also use nesting if so desired.

    • Operation:

      Input %>%
  group_by(sex) %>%
  arrange(count)
  2. Output Table B
    • Variables: sex
    • Verbs: group_by

    • Operation:

      Input %>%
  group_by(sex)
  3. Output Table C
    • Variables: name, sex
    • Verbs: group_by, arrange

    • Operation:

      Input %>%
  group_by(name, sex) %>%
  arrange(name)
  4. Output Table D
    • Variables: count
    • Verbs: summarize, sum

    • Operation:

      Input %>%
  summarise(total = sum(count)) %>%
  5. Output Table E
    • Variables: name, count
    • Verbs: group_by, select

    • Operation:

      Input %>%
  group_by(name) %>%
  select(name, count)
